Germany, year zero
The 8th of May always reminds me of the year 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was really a decisive moment in my life
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our small street, in the suburbs of western Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistance fighter, would return from the Brandenburg prison.
I wouldn't have to hide anymore like after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
The Nazis gone, the occupying powers had not yet put in place an administration.
We were pillaging the neighborhood shops. I still have a few volumes of romantic poetry recovered from a bookstore.
I was 16 years old. The occupying armies were committing all sorts of excesses.
It was difficult to get food.
My father was taken directly from his prison to the center of Berlin, and charged with setting up - from scratch - the city's energy supply bureau.
For a certain time, there was neither electricity, nor transportation, nor organized life.
Victory or liberation?
For the Germans, it was a delicate question, even if for our family it was clearly a liberation in every sense of the word.
Mais pour quoi faire ?
Pour quel avenir ?
“ You must help ”, my mother told me.
I therefore offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food products to several distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back in school.
I had a special card as a "victim of fascism", while others wore an Iron Cross earned for late services to the army.
Certainly, there were refugees from the East, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, almost everyone was crying over the disappearance of loved ones.
Yet, this stage did not last.
It's practically unbelievable, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle."
Or more precisely, the economic miracle of West Germany.
The differences between occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and above all accompanied by a new form of subjugation.
Camps of concentration like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and prisoners.
On the other hand, after a brief period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled reinforcement of autonomy.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
The democracy wasn't an empty word, and it was supported by German traditions.
Certainly, everything wasn't kindness from the occupying powers' side.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and each one wanted to consolidate "their" part of Germany.
But there are still some lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first lesson is of an economic order, and linked to the Marshall Plan.
It is perhaps regrettable, but democracy takes root more easily in an economic recovery context.
You need to have initiative, above all from individuals who want to put an end to a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with a head start.
That is why the American support through the Marshall Plan is so important.
The European Union has also helped former communist countries, and continues to accompany them in their journey.
The other lesson, of a moral order, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of the Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany did not embark on its long path by preoccupying itself with the past.
Indeed, many have described the Adenauer years after 1949 as a period of "restoration", because too many minor Nazi personalities remained in their positions.
In a certain way, the country ignored its past in order to advance towards the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and a political democracy, Germany faced its past, with a lot of success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other ravaged countries are therefore confusing.
Yet, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first the novelty, then an attempt to assume its past.
Ultimately, it is a better method.
In Europe, May 8th, 2005 is the occasion to look at the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn towards the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and therefore filled with hope.
